Article ID   : 1
Title        : SQL Injection — Techniques and Mitigations
Category     : web
Exported by  : sentinel-export-service v1.4.0
Export time  : 2026-03-01T09:00:00Z
Classification: INTERNAL

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SQL injection remains one of the most prevalent and dangerous
web application vulnerabilities, consistently appearing in
the OWASP Top 10 since its inception.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CONTENT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SQL injection occurs when untrusted data is sent to an
interpreter as part of a command or query. The attacker's
hostile data can trick the interpreter into executing
unintended commands or accessing data without authorization.

Common techniques include:
  - Classic in-band SQLi (UNION-based, error-based)
  - Blind SQLi (Boolean-based, time-based)
  - Out-of-band SQLi (DNS, HTTP exfiltration)

Remediation:
  1. Parameterized queries / prepared statements
  2. Stored procedures (with caution)
  3. Input validation and allowlisting
  4. Principle of least privilege on DB accounts

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
